<subsection xml:id="subsec-construction-of-perpendicular-lines">
        <title>Construction of Perpendicular Lines</title>
        <p>
            Perpendicular lines are lines that meet at right angle, that is, they intersect at <m>90^\circ</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            The figure below represents perpendicular lines.
        </p>

        <image width="50%">
            <shortdescription>Perpendicular lines</shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="perpendicular-lines">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw[thick,red] (-2,0) node[left] {$P$} -- (3,0) node[right]{$Q$};
                    \draw[thick,green] (0,2) node[left] {$R$} -- (0,-2) node[right]{$S$};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
        </image>

        <p>
            Lines <m>PQ</m> and <m>RS</m> are pependicular.
        </p>

        <activity>
            <p>
                Here ia an activity from <em>Math Open Reference</em> on how to construct a perpendicular lines using a pair of compasses and a ruler.
            </p>
            <p>
                Click on the link to access the activity. <url href="https://www.mathopenref.com/constperplinepoint.html" />
            </p>
    
        </activity>

        <activity>
            <statement>
            <p>
                Construct perpendicular lines in the applet below. 
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Instructions</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Using the <term>point tool (window 1)</term> in the toolbar, create two points <m>A</m> and <m>B.</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the <term>line tool (window 3),</term> create a line passing through the points <m>A</m> and <m>B.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the <term>point tool (window 1),</term> create another point <m>C</m> on the applet.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the <term>perpendicular line tool (window 4),</term> create a line, perpendicular to <m>AB</m> and passing through point <m>C</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the <term>move tool (window 1),</term> drag points  <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> and observe what happens to the line passing through point <m>C.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using the <term>angle tool (window 5),</term> measure the angle formed by the intersection of lines  <m>AB</m> and the line passing through point <m>C.</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <figure>
                <caption>Parallel lines</caption>
                <interactive xml:id="geogebra-Perpendicular-lines" platform="geogebra" width="95%" aspect="4:3">
                <slate xml:id="perpendicular-lines" surface="geogebra" material="rnuqcpav" aspect="4:3">
                    enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                    showResetIcon(true);
                </slate>
                </interactive>
            </figure>

            <p>
               What is the measure of the angle formed by the intersection of the two lines? Discuss your findings with other learners. 
            </p> 
            </statement>  
        </activity>
    
        
    </subsection>